                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00115A Pacific War/12: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Huddle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-14">February 14,
                            1942</date>.<lb/>[Received February 14—3:51 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>587. American interests—Thailand. Department’s 217, January 26, 9 p.m. Swiss
                    Consul Bangkok telegraphs February 9 following (in English): <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Minister Foreign Affairs<note n="35" xml:id="d815fn35">Sri
                                Thammathibet.</note> answered February 7 [as follows:] ‘State that
                            the treatment of American officials and nationals in Thailand has been
                            warranted by circumstances and in consonance with practice in other
                            countries. No remedy is therefore called for especially as a state of
                            war now exists between Thailand and United States of America’.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huddle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
